entry.title: High Surf Advisory issued November 13 at 8:41PM PST until November 16 at 11:00AM PST by NWS San Francisco CA
entry.summary:
* WHAT... For the Coastal Flood Advisory, coastal flooding expected. For the High Surf Advisory, large breaking waves of 12 to 15 ft with up to 20 ft along steep NW facing beaches.
* WHERE...San Francisco County.
* WHEN...For the Coastal Flood Advisory, from 7 AM Thursday to 4 PM PST Monday. For the High Surf Advisory, from 7 AM Thursday to 11 AM PST Saturday.
* IMPACTS...Dangerous swimming and surfing conditions and localized beach erosion. Large waves can sweep across the beach without warning, pulling people into the sea from rocks, jetties and beaches. Sudden immersion in cold water can result in cold water shock even for the most experienced swimmers. Cold water shock can result in dramatic changes in breathing, heart rate and blood pressure, greatly increasing the risk of drowning in rough open waters. For the coastal flood advisory, flooding of lots, parks, and roads with only isolated road closures expected.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Northwest facing beaches are most at risk for large turbulent shore break and strong currents.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued November 14 at 11:19AM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
Recent visible satellite imagery shows that the center of Tropical Storm Man-yi is nearly due north of Yap, continuing west-southwest. An outer band of torrential showers and thunderstorms is racing in toward Yap Island from the west and will be affecting the island of Yap through mid afternoon. More notable, will be a significant uptick in winds and gusts accompanied with these showers. A late-morning ASCAT pass shows 30 to 40 mph winds just northwest of Yap Island ultimately signifying the winds present and the potential for much stronger gusts.
Based on these observations, a gale warning is in effect through the afternoon, as well as a high surf advisory and coastal flood statement through tonight.
Farther east, showers and a few thunderstorms persist across Ulithi and Fais and winds have shifted out of the south. Conditions will steadily improve by mid afternoon and thereafter.
Folks across Yap State should monitor local weather forecasts the next couple of days from the National Weather Service in Guam, and for additional information from your local Weather Service Office and emergency management. Visit weather.gov/gum/PublicForecasts for the latest weather information from the National Weather Service.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued November 13 at 3:34PM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
entry.summary:
A strong and wet storm moving into Bristol Bay tonight will bring potentially hazardous conditions through Friday. Please use caution while traveling as gusty winds, blowing snow, and rain- on-snow could lead to difficult conditions.
Two rounds of strong winds are expected, with gusts 40-50 mph possible. From Thursday morning through Thursday night, east to southeast winds along the storm's front will impact communities from Lake Iliamna to as far west as Koliganek and New Stuyahok. From Thursday afternoon through Friday night, southwest to northwest winds wrapping back around the low will impact communities along the coast, from Togiak all the way to Port Heiden.
In addition to gusty winds, expect snow and blowing snow late tonight to transition to rain for much of Bristol Bay by Thursday afternoon. While blowing snow is expected, visibilities should remain above one-half mile. Forecast snow amounts range from 3-6 inches and will be affected by how quickly snow transitions to rain. Cooler air wrapping back around the low could lead to additional light snow early Friday morning.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued November 14 at 4:25AM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
Tropical Storm Man-yi will be passing just north of Yap, Ulithi and Fais today. ASCAT shows that, as expected, the south side of the storm is weaker. Nevertheless, windy conditions with occasional gale force gusts can be expected across all 3 of these islands as Man-yi passes just to the north. Also, after Man-yi passes by, southeast winds flowing into Man-yi will keep the winds and gusts elevated to just below damaging levels Friday.
Locally heavy showers will also be moving through, widespread today, numerous tonight, diminishing to scattered on Friday. Gusts will be especially prevalent near these showers, which will help to mix down higher winds aloft. After Friday, conditions will start to normalize as Man-yi passes north of Palau. For today, tonight and Friday, take any necessary action to protect crops or other property vulnerable to high winds across these islands.
